# AWS Security Guardrails

## IAM
- Never use `*` in IAM policy actions or resources in production
- Use IRSA or Pod Identity for EKS workloads; never attach broad roles to nodes
- Prefer managed policies where available; use inline only for tightly scoped exceptions
- Enforce MFA for human IAM users; use roles for service access
- Follow least-privilege: start with zero permissions, add only what's needed

## Secrets
- Never hardcode credentials, API keys, or tokens in code or config
- Use AWS Secrets Manager or SSM Parameter Store for secrets
- Mark all sensitive Terraform variables and outputs with `sensitive = true`
- Rotate secrets on a defined schedule

## Encryption
- Enable encryption at rest for all data stores (S3, EBS, RDS, DynamoDB, EFS)
- Use AWS KMS customer-managed keys for sensitive workloads
- Enforce TLS/HTTPS for all data in transit
- Enable Terraform state backend encryption

## Networking
- Default deny: use Security Groups and Network Policies as allowlists
- No `0.0.0.0/0` ingress rules on production security groups (except public ALBs on 443)
- Use private subnets for databases, EKS nodes, and internal services
- Use VPC endpoints for AWS service access from private subnets
- Enable VPC Flow Logs for audit

## S3
- Block all public access on buckets (enable `block_public_acls`, `block_public_policy`, etc.)
- Enable versioning on critical buckets
- Enable server-side encryption (SSE-S3 or SSE-KMS)
- Use bucket policies to restrict cross-account access

## Logging and Audit
- Enable CloudTrail in all regions
- Enable EKS control plane logging (API server, audit, authenticator)
- Ship logs to centralized monitoring (Datadog, CloudWatch)
- Set retention policies on all log groups
